javascript
import React, { useState, useEffect } from "react";
import { useParams } from "react-router-dom";
import {
  Container,
  Space,
  TextInput,
  Card,
  Button,
  Image,
  Group,
  Grid,
  Text,
  Title,
} from "@mantine/core";
import { RiThumbUpLine, RiThumbDownLine } from "react-icons/ri";
import { PiShareFatLight } from "react-icons/pi";

import {
  addVideoComment,
  getVideos,
  addViews,
  subscribe,
  unSubscribe,
  likeVideo,
  unlikeVideo,
} from "../api";

export default function Video() {
  const { id } = useParams();
  const [comment, setComment] = useState("");
  const [v, setV] = useState({});
  const [likes, setLikes] = useState(0);
  const [unlikes, setUnlikes] = useState(0);
  const [subscribed, setSubscribed] = useState(false);

  useEffect(() => {
    async function fetchVideoData() {
      const videoData = await getVideos(id);
      setV(videoData);
      setLikes(videoData.likes);
      setUnlikes(videoData.unlikes);
      // Check if the current user is subscribed to the video owner
      if (videoData.user && videoData.user.subscribedUsers.includes(currentUser._id)) {
        setSubscribed(true);
      } else {
        setSubscribed(false);
      }
    }
    fetchVideoData();
  }, [id]);

  const handleAddNewComment = async () => {
    // You should include your logic to add a comment here
    // Use the `comment` state to get the comment text
  };

  const handleSubscribeToggle = async () => {
    if (subscribed) {
      await unSubscribe(id);
      setSubscribed(false);
    } else {
      await subscribe(id);
      setSubscribed(true);
    }
  };

  const handleLikeToggle = async () => {
    if (likes === 0) {
      // If the user hasn't liked the video, increase likes and decrease unlikes
      setLikes(1);
      setUnlikes(0);
      await likeVideo(id);
    } else {
      // If the user has already liked the video, undo the like
      setLikes(0);
      await unlikeVideo(id);
    }
  };

  const handleUnlikeToggle = async () => {
    if (unlikes === 0) {
      // If the user hasn't unliked the video, increase unlikes and decrease likes
      setLikes(0);
      setUnlikes(1);
      await unlikeVideo(id);
    } else {
      // If the user has already unliked the video, undo the unlike
      setUnlikes(0);
      await likeVideo(id);
    }
  };

  return (
    <Container fluid>
      <Grid>
        <Grid.Col span={9}>
          {/* Video player and other video details */}
        </Grid.Col>
      </Grid>
      <Group>
        <Group position="left">
          {/* Comment input and button */}
        </Group>
      </Group>
      <Group position="right">
        {/* Like, Unlike, Subscribe buttons */}
        <Button variant="transparent" color="gray" size="md" onClick={handleLikeToggle}>
          <RiThumbUpLine /> {likes}
        </Button>
        <Button variant="transparent" color="gray" size="md" onClick={handleUnlikeToggle}>
          <RiThumbDownLine /> {unlikes}
        </Button>
        {subscribed ? (
          <Button variant="transparent" color="gray" size="md" onClick={handleSubscribeToggle}>
            Unsubscribe
          </Button>
        ) : (
          <Button variant="transparent" color="gray" size="md" onClick={handleSubscribeToggle}>
            Subscribe
          </Button>
        )}
        <Button variant="transparent" color="gray" size="md">
          <PiShareFatLight /> Share
        </Button>
      </Group>
    </Container>
  );
}

Here are the changes made to your code:

  1. Moved the likes, unlikes, and subscribed states to useState.
  2. Used useEffect to fetch video data and set the initial state when the component mounts.
  3. Implemented the handleSubscribeToggle, handleLikeToggle, and handleUnlikeToggle functions to handle subscribe, like, and unlike actions.
  4. Updated the Like, Unlike, and Subscribe buttons to toggle the state and perform the respective actions.

Please note that you need to adapt this code to your actual API functions and data structures. Make sure to handle errors and edge cases appropriately in your API functions.

To implement a video player in a React application, you can use the HTML5 <video> element. Here's a simple example of how to create a video player in a React component:

  1. Install any necessary dependencies (if not already installed):
bash
npm install react react-dom
  1. Create a new React component for the video player. You can use the following code as a starting point:
javascript
import React, { useRef } from 'react';

function VideoPlayer({ videoSource }) {
  // Create a reference to the video element
  const videoRef = useRef(null);

  // Function to play or pause the video
  const togglePlay = () => {
    if (videoRef.current.paused) {
      videoRef.current.play();
    } else {
      videoRef.current.pause();
    }
  };

  return (
    <div>
      <video ref={videoRef} controls width="640" height="360">
        <source src={videoSource} type="video/mp4" />
        Your browser does not support the video tag.
      </video>
      <button onClick={togglePlay}>Play/Pause</button>
    </div>
  );
}

export default VideoPlayer;

In this example, we create a VideoPlayer component that accepts a videoSource prop, which should be a URL to your video file. The component includes an HTML5 <video> element with controls for play, pause, and volume.

  1. Use the VideoPlayer component in your main application:
javascript
import React from 'react';
import ReactDOM from 'react-dom';
import VideoPlayer from './VideoPlayer'; // Update the path to your VideoPlayer component

function App() {
  const videoSource = 'https://example.com/your-video.mp4'; // Replace with your video URL

  return (
    <div>
      <h1>Video Player Example</h1>
      <VideoPlayer videoSource={videoSource} />
    </div>
  );
}

ReactDOM.render(<App />, document.getElementById('root'));

  1. Make sure to replace 'https://example.com/your-video.mp4' with the actual URL of your video.

  2. Finally, run your React application:

bash
npm start

This example creates a basic video player with play/pause functionality. You can further enhance it by adding more features such as fullscreen mode, volume control, and custom controls as needed for your specific use case.

If your data is a string, and you want to calculate the total from the numerical values within that string, you can use JavaScript to extract the numbers and sum them up. Here's a basic example of how you can do that:

javascript
function calculateTotalFromString(data) {
  // Use regular expression to find all numeric values in the string
  const regex = /\d+/g;
  const matches = data.match(regex);

  if (!matches) {
    return 0; // No numbers found in the string
  }

  // Convert the matched strings to numbers and sum them up
  const total = matches.reduce((acc, match) => acc + parseInt(match, 10), 0);

  return total;
}

// Example usage:
const data = "There are 5 apples and 3 oranges in the basket.";
const total = calculateTotalFromString(data);
console.log("Total:", total); // Output: Total: 8

In this example:

  1. We use a regular expression (/\d+/g) to find all sequences of digits in the input string (data).

  2. The match method is used to find all matches for the regular expression.

  3. We check if any matches were found. If not, we return 0 to indicate that no numbers were found in the string.

  4. If matches were found, we use the reduce method to convert each matched string to a number using parseInt and sum them up to calculate the total.

This code will calculate the total of all numeric values found within the input string. Please adjust it according to your specific requirements and the format of your data.

If the data you have is a string, and you want to calculate the total of numeric values within that string, you can use regular expressions to extract the numbers and then sum them up. Here's an example of how you can modify your code to achieve this:

javascript
const TotalLike = () => {
  // Your input string containing numbers
  const inputString = "Likes: 10, 20, 30";

  // Use regular expression to find all numeric values in the string
  const regex = /\d+/g;
  const matches = inputString.match(regex);

  if (!matches) {
    return 0; // No numbers found in the string
  }

  // Convert the matched strings to numbers and sum them up
  const total = matches.reduce((acc, match) => acc + parseInt(match, 10), 0);

  return total;
};

// Example usage:
const totalLikes = TotalLike();
console.log("Total Likes:", totalLikes); // Output: Total Likes: 60

In this modified code:

  1. inputString represents your input data, which is a string containing numbers.

  2. We use a regular expression (/\d+/g) to find all sequences of digits (numbers) in the inputString.

  3. The match method is used to find all matches for the regular expression.

  4. We check if any matches were found. If not, we return 0 to indicate that no numbers were found in the string.

  5. If matches were found, we use the reduce method to convert each matched string to a number using parseInt and sum them up to calculate the total.

This code will calculate the total of all numeric values found within the input string. Make sure to replace the inputString with your actual string data.

It seems you have a route in an Express.js application that handles subscription to a user. This route is designed to allow one user to subscribe to another user and update their respective data accordingly.

Here's a breakdown of what this route does:

  1. It's a PUT request to the endpoint /subscribe/:id, where :id is a parameter representing the ID of the user to subscribe to.

  2. It uses an authMiddleware function to ensure that the user making the request is authenticated.

  3. It queries the current user's information using request.user.id and updates their subscribedUsers array by pushing the ID of the user they want to subscribe to. This updates the list of users they are subscribed to.

  4. It then queries the information of the user being subscribed to (with the ID request.params.id) and increments their subscribers count by 1. This keeps track of how many users are subscribed to this particular user.

  5. Finally, it sends a success response with a status code of 200 and a message indicating that the subscription was successful.

This route is designed to handle user subscriptions and update the relevant user data in the database accordingly. It's important to make sure that you have appropriate error handling and validation in place to handle any potential issues that may arise during this process.
